social_posts.post_text:
The Singapore Botanic Gardens is a 164-year-old tropical garden. It is the first and only tropical botanic garden on the UNESCO’s World Heritage List.

The National Orchid Garden, which is located within the main gardens, is at the forefront of #orchid studies and a pioneer in the cultivation of hybrids, complementing the nation's status as a major exporter of cut orchids. Aided by the equatorial climate, it houses the largest orchid collection of 1,200 species and 2,000 hybrids.

In 1981, the hybrid climbing orchid, Vanda Miss Joaquim, was chosen as the country's national flower.

🫧 Do you ever have those days when the critic in your head makes you feel as if you are not enough. Things haven't manifested for you. You feel like you're never going to make all your dreams come true. 

As painful as it is, I feel it's a natural part of drive and desire. The emotion isn't particularly pleasant, but it's just a guide on your journey. 

In contrast to your critic, there is this other voice. Mine is particularly cute, and when I'm especially mean to that kind creature and inner child, it really breaks my heart. That voice is like a 4 year old who believes in everything and is your biggest cheerleader. It's that voice that says, " You can do it!" 

That voice deserves a lot more respect than we give it credit. I love you! You got this, xo 💋

Performance art vs. Making sellable art

Ideally, in my practice, the performance is as strong as the final piece. However, that isn't always the case. Generally, one takes a backseat depending on the intention and scenario. Most of my live performances are just a performance, and there is nothing to show or sell afterward. 

In the studio, I have the ample time to set up and create what it is I have planned in my mind with zero distractions. I can pause and stop, look at what my body is creating, and continue to conceptualize my desired composition and flow of the final artwork.

Exploring the DiVA exhibit at the @vamuseum

"Compliment or criticism, aspiration or condemnation, today the word 'diva' holds a myriad or meanings. Taken from the Latin for `goddess', the term became widely used in the 19th century to describe an exceptional female opera singer. But over the years, the definition of a diva has expanded, been subverted, tarnished
and, ultimately, embraced. Spanning opera, film, music, and the stage, DiVA celebrates how trailblazing artists, regardless of gender have challenged the status quo and pushed the boundaries of their art to unapologetically own their diva crown. Divided into two acts, creation and reclamation, the exhibition puts these iconic performers center stage, exploring how the word has been redefined and celebrating the people that embody it.

In Act 2, we meet the original divas, those divinely talented opera singers of the 19th century, and the generations they inspired. Against a backdrop of changing attitudes to femininity, power, and creativity, these leadling ladies conquered the stage and the screen, campaigning for equality along the way. Although worshipped by their adoring fans, they also ehcountered criticism and distain for daring to step outside the box. The multifaceted diva was born."

@kudashkina_bodyart and I met around 2010 at a birthday party. About a year later, we truly connected as friends and creatives. I loved being her muse and had so much fun conceptualizing videos and designs with her. Looking back on our body of work, you can tell how much innocent fun we were having in this magical world we devised for ourselves. 🌈✨️🎨💖

2 years ago January, I moved / drove to LA. I was in a very serious relationship of 4.5 years when everything fell apart. Without a home anymore, I stayed in California house and cat sitting until Burning Man. 

I had to put myself in a mental and spiritual state of abundance. In a lot of ways, you can call it delusion, but it worked. If I wanted to manifest my dream life and be cared for by the universe, I had to be on a completely different frequency to the one I was on.

Not only was I running towards my dreams, but running away from the broken ones. The pain always catches up, tears flow, you let go and face the music. It's all a part of the growth and healing journey. 

The last two years have been one of the most adventurous and magical times of my life. I am tired, though. On every level. I miss having a place to call home, I miss having a studio. I miss my bed, sewing machines, disco ball, and yummy world (lol) 

I've always had a special communication when listening to what the universe is telling me. I'm excited because I'm about to start a new chapter and settle down in Montréal for a minute. It will be nice to have the time and space to focus on my health, career, and fitness goals. 2024, the year of the dragon is going to be everything 🐉 I hope the year brings all of you blessings and abundance.

9 years ago, I went on a vision quest. I participated in a Hopi ceremony called a Kiva where you desend a ladder into the ground layered with seeds and intention. The Kiva is known as the womb of Mother Earth. A place where you can connect to the heavens. You call in your spirit guides, elders, ancestors, and Kachina's. 

My intentions were set, and my prayers were honest. The spirits had been called in. The space was full of tobacco, and the drumming and singing around the fire was so clear. I closed my eyes and saw myself naked running up invisible spiral stairs with huge white feather wings on my back, surrounded by darkness and stars.  Every time I took a step, hands would appear to support me and take me higher.

It felt like I was dreaming, but I was sober and awake. It felt like I was talking to my spirit family, our spirit family
